{{engineering-stub}}

In [[metallurgy]], '''exfoliation corrosion''' (also called lamellar corrosion<ref name=":0" />) is a severe type<ref>{{cite web|title=Exfoliation Corrosion|url=https://cwst.com/shot-peening/reasons-to-shot-peen/exfoliation-corrosion/}}</ref> of [[intergranular corrosion]] that raises surface grains from metal by forming [[corrosion|corrosion products]] at [[Crystallite|grain boundaries]] under the surface. It is frequently found on [[extrusion|extruded]] sections where grain thickness is not as thick as the rolled grain.  It can affect aircraft structures <ref>{{cite web|title=Exfoliation Corrosion and Pitting Corrosion and Their Role in Fatigue Predictive Modeling: State-of-the-Art Review|url=https://www.hindawi.com/journals/ijae/2012/191879/}}</ref>, marine vessels <ref>{{cite web|title=Different Types of Corrosion|url=http://www.corrosionclinic.com/types_of_corrosion/aluminium_exfoliation_corrosion.htm}}</ref>, heaters <ref name=":0">{{cite web|title=Lamellar Corrosion or Exfoliation?|url=https://www.nace.org/Corrosion-Central/Corrosion-101/Lamellar-Corrosion-or-Exfoliation-/}}</ref>and other objects.

